\begin{definition}
A starting method $S$ defined by the generalized Runge--Kutta methods \eqref{eq:530a}, for $i = 1, 2, \dots, r$, is `degenerate' if $b_0^{(i)} = 0$, for $i = 1, 2, \dots, r$, and `non-degenerate' otherwise.
\end{definition}

context_latex:
\paragraph{Context}
A starting method $S$ is a sequence of $r$ generalized Runge--Kutta methods used to initialize a general linear method. Degeneracy depends on whether all these methods have a zero coefficient $b_0^{(i)}$.

Variables:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $S$: a starting method, defined as a sequence $S_1, S_2, \dots, S_r$ of generalized Runge--Kutta methods.
    \item $r$: the number of generalized Runge--Kutta methods in $S$.
    \item $S_i$: the $i$-th generalized Runge--Kutta method in $S$, for $i = 1, 2, \dots, r$.
    \item $b_0^{(i)}$: a coefficient for the $i$-th method $S_i$.
\end{itemize}

Referenced equations:
\begin{itemize}
    \item (530a): the definition of the generalized Runge--Kutta methods constituting $S$.
\end{itemize}
